<body>
  <h1>Project Sentinel MVP Plan</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">A recruiter-worthy MVP strategy for building an AI reliability project under limited time.</p>

  <h2>1. Executive Recommendation</h2>
  <p>
    Project Sentinel is a strong project idea, but the MVP must be narrowed sharply. The best version is not a full AI observability platform, a chatbot, or a generic dashboard. The strongest MVP is a research-grade reliability detection engine with a small demo interface.
  </p>
  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>Recommended MVP:</strong> Sentinel Drift Lab</p>
    <p>
      A system that detects when an LLM's semantic reliability is degrading over time using unlabeled behavioral signals.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>2. Core Project Claim</h2>
  <p>
    Sentinel detects semantic degradation in LLM outputs before accuracy labels are available by fusing stability, semantic drift, and uncertainty-proxy signals into a Reliability Degradation Score.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is stronger than simply saying, "I built an AI monitoring dashboard." It shows machine learning, NLP, evaluation design, and AI infrastructure thinking.
  </p>

  <h2>3. What The MVP Should Build</h2>

  <h3>3.1 Dataset Stream Simulator</h3>
  <p>
    Use benchmark datasets to simulate production-like time windows. The goal is to create a controlled environment where normal and degraded model behavior can be compared.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>TruthfulQA:</strong> factuality, hallucination, and truthfulness reliability.</li>
    <li><strong>GSM8K or MMLU subset:</strong> reasoning and task reliability.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Example production windows:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Window 1-3: normal model behavior.</li>
    <li>Window 4-6: degraded model behavior.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Possible degradation scenarios:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Prompt corruption.</li>
    <li>Context truncation.</li>
    <li>Weaker model replacement.</li>
    <li>Temperature increase.</li>
    <li>Instruction conflict.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3.2 Signal Extraction Engine</h3>
  <p>
    For each time window, Sentinel should compute multiple reliability signals instead of depending on one fragile metric.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Semantic consistency:</strong> ask the same or paraphrased prompt multiple times and measure embedding similarity between answers.</li>
    <li><strong>Response stability:</strong> measure how much answers change under small prompt perturbations.</li>
    <li><strong>Embedding drift:</strong> compare current output embeddings with baseline window embeddings.</li>
    <li><strong>Uncertainty proxy:</strong> track hedging words, refusal rate, answer length variance, and self-contradiction rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Task compliance:</strong> detect missing final answers, invalid numeric answers, or irrelevant answers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3.3 Semantic Reliability Score</h3>
  <p>
    The initial scoring method should be simple, explainable, and testable. Avoid overengineering the first version.
  </p>
  <pre>SRS = w1 * consistency_score
    + w2 * stability_score
    + w3 * inverse_embedding_drift
    + w4 * confidence_proxy_score
    + w5 * task_compliance_score</pre>
  <p>
    Degradation can then be detected using thresholding, z-score anomaly detection, Isolation Forest, or One-Class SVM.
  </p>

  <h3>3.4 Evaluation</h3>
  <p>
    Evaluation is what will make this project look serious. The project should not only show graphs; it should prove whether Sentinel actually detects degradation.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Detection accuracy.</li>
    <li>Precision.</li>
    <li>Recall.</li>
    <li>False positive rate.</li>
    <li>Detection lead time.</li>
    <li>Robustness across degradation scenarios.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Recommended ablation study:</p>
  <pre>Only embedding drift: X%
Only semantic consistency: Y%
Only stability: Z%
Full Sentinel score: Best result</pre>

  <h3>3.5 Demo Interface</h3>
  <p>
    The UI should be small and secondary. Use Streamlit for speed. The interface should communicate the experiment clearly without pretending to be a complete enterprise platform.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Reliability score over time.</li>
    <li>Detected degradation point.</li>
    <li>Signal breakdown.</li>
    <li>Sample degraded outputs.</li>
    <li>Normal vs degraded output comparison.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>4. What Not To Build In The MVP</h2>
  <div class="warning">
    <p>
      These features should be avoided initially because they will consume time without improving the core technical value.
    </p>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li>Full observability platform.</li>
    <li>Tracing infrastructure.</li>
    <li>User accounts or authentication.</li>
    <li>Cloud deployment complexity.</li>
    <li>Chatbot interface.</li>
    <li>Too many datasets.</li>
    <li>Too many models.</li>
    <li>Generic enterprise dashboard with weak algorithmic depth.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>5. Recruiter Value</h2>
  <p>
    This MVP demonstrates skills that are much stronger than a common student project.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Natural Language Processing.</li>
    <li>Embedding analysis.</li>
    <li>Statistical drift detection.</li>
    <li>LLM evaluation.</li>
    <li>Reliability engineering.</li>
    <li>Experiment design.</li>
    <li>AI infrastructure thinking.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The key differentiation is unlabeled semantic degradation inference. Existing observability tools already provide tracing, dashboards, and evaluation workflows. Sentinel should focus on detecting silent semantic degradation when ground-truth labels are not continuously available.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Recommended Timeline</h2>
  <h3>7-Day MVP</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>One dataset.</li>
    <li>One model.</li>
    <li>Three degradation scenarios.</li>
    <li>Reliability score implementation.</li>
    <li>Streamlit visualization.</li>
    <li>README with results.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>14-Day Strong Version</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Two datasets.</li>
    <li>Ablation study.</li>
    <li>Multiple detection methods.</li>
    <li>Clean result plots.</li>
    <li>Technical report.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>21-Day Portfolio Version</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Polished GitHub repository.</li>
    <li>Architecture diagram.</li>
    <li>Experiment table.</li>
    <li>Short demo video.</li>
    <li>Blog-style explanation: Detecting Silent LLM Degradation Without Ground Truth Labels.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>7. Suggested Final Project Title</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Project Sentinel: Unlabeled Semantic Degradation Detection for Production LLMs</strong>
  </p>

  <h2>8. Resume Bullet</h2>
  <p>
    Built an AI reliability framework that detects semantic degradation in LLM outputs without ground-truth labels by combining embedding drift, response stability, self-consistency, and uncertainty-proxy signals; evaluated across induced degradation scenarios with precision, recall, false-positive rate, and detection lead time.
  </p>

  <h2>9. Final Direction</h2>
  <p>
    The strongest path is to build a focused, measurable AI reliability engine first and add a lightweight interface only after the core experiment works. This keeps the project technical, credible, and useful for internship applications.
  </p>
</body>
</html>
